For all complex numbers $z$, let \[f(z) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
z^{2}&\text{ if }z\text{ is not real}, \\
-z^2 &\text{ if }z\text{ is real}.
\end{array}
\right.\]Find $f(f(f(f(1+i))))$. ||| We start by calculating $f(1+i)$. Since $1+i$ is not real, we use the first case and get $f(1+i) = (1+i)^2 = 1 + 2i - 1 = 2i$. Now we calculate $f(f(1+i))=f(2i)$. Because $2i$ is also not real, we again use the first case: $f(2i) = (2i)^2 = 4i^2 = -4$. Next, we compute $f(f(f(1+i))) = f(-4)$. Since $-4$ is real, we switch to the second case: $f(-4) = -(-4)^2 = 16$. Finally, we need to find $f(f(f(f(1+i}))) = f(16)$. Again, since $16$ is real, we have $f(16) = -(16)^2 = -256$. Thus, my answer is $\boxed{-256}$.

